<DOCNO> AP890530-0001 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
police fought armed bands in the 
capital and hungry mobs in rosario on tuesday and the death toll 
reached 11 officials talked of handing out free food to stop 
looting sparked by soaring inflation 
six more people were reported killed tuesday in the buenos 
aires suburbs of san miguel and quilmes looters loading food into 
trucks threw stones at police who tried to stop them and police 
fired rubber bullets back killing four local news agencies said 
it was part of a riot along a 120block stretch in which looters 
broke windows and emptied shelves in furniture stores bars sports 
and shoe stores a bus driver tried to prevent his bus from being 
stolen and was fatally shot 
in the buenos aires suburb of moreno a sixth person was killed 
tuesday under confusing circumstances local news agencies 
repoted 
by tuesday night the roving bands of youths that prompted many 
stores to close had scattered and interior minister juan carlos 
pugliese said he would not deploy federal troops 
but in rosario argentinas thirdbiggest city and the countrys 
meatpacking capital armed bands drove through deserted streets 
shot at police stations and looted private homes as well as stores 
they left practically nothing standing mayor santos mauro 
of the suburban rosario town of villa gobernador galvez said 
they overwhelmed everything supermarkets shops shoe stores 
family homes were damaged 
lesser scale looting was reported in the western city of 
mendoza the countrys fourthbiggest the provincial capitals of 
la plata and tucuman and about a dozen working class suburbs of 
buenos aires 
in buenos aires on tuesday bombs damaged buildings housing two 
political parties noise bombs set off in the central business 
district injured six passersby but by tuesday night the bombings 
had ended 
five people were killed earlier this week in rosario including 
four men who were shot and a woman who suffered a heart attack and 
60 were injured by tear gas rubber bullets stones and clubs more 
than 1000 people have been arrested in rosario and about 500 
looters arrested in other cities 
congress debated the 30day state of siege declared monday by 
president raul alfonsin 
four young men dragged a side of beef from a supermarket in 
rosario a city of 1 million 185 miles north of the capital one 
cut it into quarters with a knife and said were not looking for 
whisky or wine as they say others are doing we just want 
something to eat 
looters walked past police and broke into food stores before 
police clamped down 
thank god today i can eat an elderly woman shouted as she 
rushed out of a grocery store with looted goods 
about 1000 additional border police were deployed in rosario 
argentinas thirdlargest city and the scene of the worst looting 
and clashes the past three days 
the lootings began last week when a supermarket in mendoza the 
countrys fourthbiggest city was firebombed and police in 
cordoba the secondlargest confiscated boxes of molotov cocktails 
months of economic chaos have brought the pay of many 
argentines in terms of equivalent buying power to 25 a month or 
less monthly inflation is estimated at 70 percent for may the 
national currency has been devalued by 90 percent since february 
and thousands of people have been thrown out of work 
on sunday alfonsin revealed his plans for stabilizing the 
economy his radical civic union lost the may 14 national elections 
to the peronists but there is a sevenmonth lag between election 
and inauguration 
hunger marches were held in two cities monday and stores were 
looted in more than a dozen in tucuman 600 boxes of powdered milk 
were stolen from a warehouse 
government officials in the biggest provinces scrambled to set 
up free food programs in an effort to forestall violence 
its a first step and we know it will be insufficient 
because the magnitude of the crisis overwhelms the capacity of 
provincial finances said buenos aires province official mario 
cafiero 
cordoba has given tons of food to the needy and mendoza plans 
to do the same 
in rosario schools were closed and shopkeepers bricked up glass 
fronts to protect their property all business activity including 
movies bars restaurants was ordered to cease at 6 pm 
at one store that had been looted three times owner daniel 
rodriguez said i have two alternatives i can put the little i 
have left in the street and give it away or i can just set fire to 
it all 
national government officials have blamed the looting on leftist 
agitators citing the degree of organization and the theft of 
nonfood items but have not accused specific organizations 
vice president victor martinez blamed groups that do not want 
to see the current government end its term and another 
constitutional government begin 
presidentelect carlos menem is to be installed dec 10 under 
the constitution his refusal last week to assume office early 
contributed to a political paralysis that leaves alfonsins 
government little credibility and gives the governmentelect little 
power 
menem said monday he supported the state of siege as did 
antonio cafiero president of the peronist party and governor of 
buenos aires province 
foreign exchange houses were allowed to open for the first time 
in five business days tuesday and banks resumed operations with 
restrictions 
many exchange houses refused to sell dollars at the official 
rate of 175 australs bank withdrawals were limited to 40000 
australs 
</TEXT>
