<TEXT>
west european leaders gave a quick 
stamp of approval to the plan drawn up by president bush to reduce 
sharply us and soviet troops stationed in europe by 1993 
their formal approval will come today in the communique the nato 
leaders will issue after concluding the twoday 40th anniversary 
summit of the 16nation military alliance 
but the sweeping bush proposal clearly aimed at seizing the 
arms control initiative from soviet president mikhail gorbachev 
was greeted at mondays opening session by unanimous praise 
british prime minister margaret thatcher a staunch us ally 
said the offer had transformed the summit which had been 
overshadowed by a nagging dispute over the future role of 
shortrange nuclear arms in europe 
nato foreign ministers early today arrived at compromise 
language to solve that dispute 
west german chancellor helmut kohl called bushs initiative a 
farsighted step that impressively affirmed the united states 
leadership 
president bush has today paved the way for further success of 
our alliance kohl told his colleagues 
the western leaders have been dogged in recent weeks by a fight 
touched off by a german demand for nato to enter into early talks 
with the sovietled warsaw pact on reducing shortrange nuclear 
arms in europe 
the united states and britain had opposed immediate bargaining 
on those weapons arguing that the alliance should first focus its 
attention on slashing conventional or nonnuclear arms in europe 
the compromise formula worked out by the foreign ministers in a 
postmidnight skull session links the start of shortrange missile 
talks to completion of a conventional arms treaty it also 
stipulates that no nuclear missiles would be pulled out until the 
conventional reductions were completed 
even before the ministers fashioned their negotiating strategy 
european officials said the bush troop initiative had made it 
easier to resolve the missile dispute 
the sting is out of the problem said dutch prime minister 
ruud lubbers it is not of the same urgency any more 
canadian prime minister brian mulroney urged the other allies to 
back the bush proposals and turn them over to nato experts to flesh 
out over the next 60 to 90 days 
the plans would then be put down on the negotiating table at the 
conventional arms talks between nato and the sevennation warsaw 
pact the bargaining which began in early march in vienna covers 
an area spanning the atlantic ocean to the ural mountains in the 
soviet union 
spanish foreign minister franciso fernandez ordonez said bush 
had given a fresh push to those discussions 
this proposal he said would reduce the possibility of a 
surprise attack by the warsaw pact 
a senior administration official briefing reporters under cloak 
of anonymity said the response was even warmer than anything we 
had reason to expect 
in moscow the soviet news agency tass said the american offer 
came from a bush administration under serious criticism from the 
public for the lack of any disarmament initiatives at a time when 
the soviet union has launched a peace offensive 
bush called for washington and moscow to agree to trim their 
troops stationed in europe to 275000 on each side 
this would amount to a 20 percent cut in us combat troops in 
europe reducing overall us troop strength by about 10 percent 
there are about 150000 us combat troops in europe and more than 
150000 support personnel 
the soviets have an estimated 625000 troops in eastern and 
central europe gorbachev has already offered to cut to 350000 and 
proposed equal ceilings of nato and warsaw pact forces of 135 
million 
bush also called on the kremlin to make good on a recent 
gorbachev proposal to set ceilings on conventional arms 20000 
tanks 28000 armored troop carriers and 16500 to 24000 artillery 
pieces the precise number depending on how those weapons are 
defined 
according to nato the west has 16424 main battle tanks and the 
warsaw pact has 51500 heavy tanks with announced cuts to reduce 
that number to 39500 
the president also pressed for reductions in combat airplanes 
and helicopters to levels 15 percent below the current nato levels 
or about 5440 for each side 
all equipment that was pulled back would be destroyed 
the french and the british western europes only nuclear 
powers immediately said they would resist any attempt to include 
their dualcapable aircraft which can fire both conventional and 
nuclear weapons in the bush arms plan 
</TEXT>
