<TEXT>
mining companies seeking to revive a 5 percent 
cap on the royalties they pay to help finance arizona public 
schools suffered an 80 defeat in the supreme court today 
the justices upheld a ruling by the states highest court that 
the cap established by the state legislature in 1941 violates 
federal law 
todays decision is a victory for the arizona education 
association a teachers union and those taxpayers who challenged 
the cap 
the case now will return to a state trial court which was 
ordered by the state supreme court to determine what further 
relief if any is appropriate 
the dispute has its roots in arizonas drive for statehood the 
1910 law in which congress authorized people in arizona and new 
mexico to form state governments placed strict controls over how 
the new states could use land set aside to help finance public 
schools 
nearly 10 million acres in arizona was covered by the law and 
the state arizona was admitted into the union of states in 1912 
was required to obtain true value in disposing of the land and 
its products 
at issue in the case decided today was whether a 1927 law passed 
by congress loosened those strict controls lawyers for the mining 
companies argued that it had but the high court today disagreed 
the arizona legislature in 1941 permitted the state to lease the 
trust lands for a royalty of 5 percent of the net value of the 
minerals produced from the land 
the lawsuit filed by arizona education association and certain 
taxpayers contended successfully that the 5 percent cap allows a 
giveaway of resources intended to be used for the states schools 
they said royalty rates could be determined by competitive 
bidding administrative rules or casebycase negotiation they 
also urged that royalties be based on gross mineral value to bar 
companies from avoiding having to pay the state anything if costs 
exceed mineral values 
the states royalty payments from the trust lands declined from 
nearly 8 million in 1980 to 13 million in 1986 
mining companies have paid from 6 to 14 percent in royalties on 
land owned by indian tribes in arizona the justices were told 
writing for the court justice anthony m kennedy said the 
sale or lease of mineral lands granted to the state of arizona 
under these federal statutes must substantially conform to the 
mandatory requirements set out in the 1910 law 
he said the arizona supreme court was correct in declaring 
the 5 percent cap invalid as to nonhydrocarbon mineral leases 
kennedys 25page opinion included a 17page discussion on why 
the justices hold the proper authority what lawyers call 
jurisdiction to decide the case 
justices william j brennan byron r white thurgood marshall 
harry a blackmun and john paul stevens joined kennedys opinion on 
the merits of the case 
chief justice william h rehnquist and antonin scalia voted to 
dismiss the case due to a lack of jurisdiction which also would 
have resulted in a loss for the mining companies 
justice sandra day oconnor the courts only native arizonan 
did not participate in the decision 
the case is asarco vs kadish 871661 
