<TEXT>
about 200 americans are quietly talking trade 
with their chinese counterparts this week amid student protesters 
clamoring for democracy and political factions trying to purge 
rivals they blame for the turmoil 
the 2nd uschina joint session on industry trade and economic 
development opened monday with far less fanfare than last year but 
participants said tuesday they were undeterred by the political 
troubles 
there isnt any business uncertainty on the american side 
said william kinch chairman of grace china ltd a subsidiary of 
the new yorkbased accounting firm wr grace the chinese are 
saying this will have no bearing on economic policy in the future 
chinese participants have stressed the point that all sides to 
the internal political debate are keeping the door open to the 
west said washington attorney michael zacharia former assistant 
secretary for export administration in the commerce department 
but the sixweek prodemocracy student movement and the ensuing 
power struggle among the chinese leadership has cast a long shadow 
over the conference 
last year it opened in the great hall of the people chinas 
seat of government with a childrens drum and cymbal corps 
greeting 1000 us businesssmen and premier li peng giving a 
welcoming address 
the great hall was ruled out this year the adjacent tiananmen 
square is occupied by thousands of students many demanding lis 
resignation for imposing martial law on beijing to put down their 
protests 
the american side organized by people to people international 
citizen ambassador program of spokane wash decided to cancel an 
economic summit when it became obvious chinas top leaders had 
other things on their minds 
a chinese trade show had to be called off because exhibitors 
from outside beijing couldnt get their goods to the capital a 
special train arranged to take the americans to other chinese 
cities was canceled although regional visits will go ahead as 
planned 
only about 200 americans mostly from small and mediumsized 
businesses made the trip well below original estimates 
there was a lot of uncertainty among american delegates before 
getting here said people to people chairman norman swanson 
adding he was impressed with the perseverance of those who 
decided to come 
stephen e guisinger a university of texas professor who heads 
the joint center for chinaus management studies quoted one of 
his fellow delegates as saying the political crisis was a stress 
test for the chinese 
its a good opportunity to see how china reacts under 
stress he said 
guisinger also argued it is inevitable that china adopt a more 
open political system as it opens its economy to the outside world 
the current upheaval he said could have positive results 
the americans predicted us investment in china will fall in 
the short run but blamed that more on an economic austerity policy 
in effect since last fall to cool off the overheated economy and 
bring down a 30 percent rate of inflation 
guisinger said americans selling goods china badly needs or 
negotiating longterm business links should have no problems but 
the businessman hoping to sell 100 million in computers in the 
next two years is going to run into difficulties 
</TEXT>
