<DOCNO> AP890530-0106 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
wooden bridges long ago relegated to 
picture postcard status are making a comeback as engineers merge 
todays technologies with the material of yesteryear 
wood is so commonplace says john crist director of the 
us forest service timber bridge program it just hasnt been 
sexy like steel and concrete 
with deteriorating bridges on the increase and state and federal 
highway funds being squeezed timber is getting a new look from 
engineers and government planners who for years have favored 
concrete and steel 
crist and others say new designs for wood allow timber bridges 
to support the same 40ton trucks as concrete and steel they also 
claim wood will last longer and is cheaper to build and maintain 
but those who would make wood the product of choice must 
overcome the fact that it has been dismissed as outdated for so 
long 
thats our toughest nut to crack most of our engineers in 
this country have been trained in steel and concrete crist said 
timber bridges have long been used in the nations most remote 
areas and vermonts covered bridges have been in service for more 
than a century but state and local officials have shied away from 
using timber in federally funded projects because federal standards 
are geared to concrete and steel 
what weve had is a whole lot of cadillacs where chevys and 
fords will do fine simply because thats the way we can get these 
funds said dennis borchardt a resource economist and executive 
director of the george aiken research conservation and development 
area in randolph 
the campaign to bring back timber is being fueled by a 33 
million federal program designed to construct 80 timber bridges in 
30 states by next year 
the goals behind the federal initiative are to expand the market 
for less popular types of wood stimulate the local economy and 
eventually create standard timber bridge designs easy enough for 
local road crews to construct crist said 
to boost wood as the material of choice in vermont a 
demonstration bridge is being built in norwich with completion 
scheduled to coincide with a midjune conference on timber bridges 
also this year the state is sponsoring what officials say is 
the first bridge design competition since 1889 when a jury chose a 
design for the harlem river bridge in new york city now called the 
washington bridge 
the state competition is intended to stimulate design proposals 
with an emphasis on the use of vermont materials for the hundreds 
of town bridges that need to be replaced 
federal experts say as many as half the nations 550000 bridges 
are deficient in some way supporters of timber bridges say most of 
those are short to medium spans many of which would be suited for 
timber 
the bridge in norwich in eastern vermont uses one of the newest 
construction methods known as stressed deck construction which 
was developed in canada when bridges made of wood glued together 
began coming apart 
the construction uses panels of wood with steel rods running 
through them and allows smaller trees to be used in building the 
bridge 
we dont have a lot of very large trees left any more if we 
want to cross a 75foot river we have to find other ways to do 
it said barry dickson a timber bridge engineer 
for some of those involved in the new bridge projects the most 
compelling argument for returning to wood is not its cost or 
availability it is woods beauty 
in the middle of the national forest it would be nice not to 
have steel and concrete said jim moore of new hampshires 
municipal highway division 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

