<TEXT>
sales of new homes were up a strong 109 
percent in april the government said tuesday but housing 
economists say the industry will remain on the downside at least 
into summer because of high interest rates 
the increase in sales to 620000 units on a seasonally adjusted 
annual basis was due to an aberration in sales in february and 
march when they dropped 109 percent and 104 percent the 
economists said 
the april increase was the steepest since a 139 percent jump in 
february 1988 
analysts were divided over how soon the housing market would 
pick up 
we view the market tone as generally weakening said david 
seiders chief economist for the national association of home 
builders 
were looking for further weakening in certainly the third 
quarter perhaps the fourth as well he said 
but richard peach deputy chief economist for the mortgage 
bankers association said that while the industry still is in a 
slowing trend the second quarter will be the trough 
as lower intrest rates kick in sales will increase as the 
summer goes on peach said 
fixedrate mortgage interest reached a peak of 1122 percent in 
march and began to drop in april averaging between 1099 percent 
and 1111 percent according to a weekly national survey by the 
federal home loan mortgage corp 
rates had been rising for over a year as the federal reserve 
tightened credit in an attempt to stem inflation 
david w berson chief economist for the federal national 
mortgage association said he too thinks housing activity will 
increase as mortgage rates continue to fall 
we dont expect a tremendous surge in housing activity but we 
do expect it to bounce back a little bit from the levels we saw in 
february and march he said were likely to see new home sales 
between 600000 and 650000 on a seasonally adjusted annual basis 
over the next several months 
the april sales level compares with new home purchases totaling 
676000 in 1988 and 671000 in 1987 
john tuccillo chief economist for the national association of 
realtors also sees a slight pickup in sales activity later this 
year 
we anticipate new home sales will pick up slightly during the 
second half of 1989 ending the year with a sales total of about 
640000 he said 
the west paced the april rebound with a 313 percent increase in 
sales to 193000 it was followed by a 212 percent jump to 234000 
units in the south 
sales fell 68 percent to 96000 homes in the midwest and 172 
percent also to 96000 in the northeast 
the falloff in sales in the northeast where housing costs 
generally are highest was the major cause for a 9000 drop in the 
median price of homes to 117000 last month the analysts said 
it was the first medianprice decline since a 2500 decrease 
last november the median price represents the level where half of 
the homes cost more and half less 
the average price which is affected by sales of expensive 
homes totaled 145700 in april down 4800 from the previous 
month 
