<TEXT>
burmas military government has changed 
the countrys official name to reflect its ethnic diversity a move 
apparently aimed at cooling unrest a diplomatic source said 
a military spokesman announced last week that the official name 
union of burma was being changed to the union of myanma to 
reflect that there are other ethnic groups beside the burmese 
majority a western diplomat in rangoon said 
for four decades a dozen ethnic guerrilla groups controlling 
vast rural areas have been fighting for greater autonomy from the 
government 
last year the government dropped the socialist republic 
from the countrys name to show its willingness to end a quarter 
century of ruinous rigid socialist policies 
the diplomat reached by telephone from bangkok said public 
reaction to the announcement has been apathetic 
the government has made a series of mostly superficial 
tentative changes in the economy and the political system since 
millions of people marched in the streets nationwide last year to 
demand democracy the military ended the marches by shooting dead 
thousands of peaceful demonstrators 
a general election has been promised for may 1990 but 
authorities have constantly harassed the main opposition party the 
national league for democracy 
the national democratic front guerrilla coalition combines 10 
ethnic groups opposed to the government of gen saw maung and 
claims to control half of burma the largest single guerrilla group 
is the karen national union 
