producers have been a little late in realizing the achievements 
they can get from advertising 
the national advertising budget is only 3 million for an 
industry which last year had 31 billion in sales down from 41 
billion in 1984 
meanwhile the producers biggest competitors cereal makers 
spend hundreds of millions of dollars annually on advertising said 
raffel 
egg producers have a 2cent checkoff for each dozen eggs to 
finance national advertising and are awaiting usda approval for a 
5cent checkoff 
last year was an absolutely terrible year for producers 
said ken klippen vice president of united egg producers in 
atlanta farmers were losing money on every dozen eggs they were 
producing as wholesale prices fluctuated from 50 cents to 75 
cents a dozen 
the drought raised the cost of feed ingredients corn and 
soybean meal while consumption continued downward klippen said 
the industry has lost money five years in this decade including 
280 million in 1988 according to agricultural economist lee 
schrader of purdue university this year schrader forecasts a 
modest profit of 115 million on sales of 4 billion at the 
wholesale level 
the last good year for the industry was 1986 when it made 69 
cents per dozen for a 400 million profit 
the profits this year probably wont come as a result of the 
cholesterol reports klippen said 
its too early to say what effects those reports will have 
he said theyre very positive were trying to change the 
perception of eggs as high in cholesterol but its very 
laborious especially when the consumers are bombarded with 
promotions of products that are low in cholesterol and 
cholesterol free everybody hears this buzzword 
undoubtedly the health issue has been a factor in some of the 
decline in use of eggs but its very difficult to separate that 
out of other factors such as changing lifestyles schrader said 
its not clear what the issue has been changing cholesterol 
levels are bound to have some impact but not a large amount 
the consolidation of the industry nationally there are about 
1600 producers down from 6000 in 1979 may help the national 
advertising effort raffel said 
there are fewer producers to make understand the value of 
advertising he said the larger ones are more sophisticated 
despite consolidation and the decline in annual per capita 
consumption from 278 eggs in 1979 to 242 eggs last year it was 
321 eggs in 1960 when big breakfasts were still fashionable and 
cholesterol wasnt a major concern the number of egglaying hens 
has remained fairly constant in recent years at about 235 million 
