<TEXT>
the district of columbia council on tuesday 
passed emergency legislation designed to prevent the extradition of 
a teenager facing a possible death sentence in alabama 
supporters of the measure which will remain in effect for 90 
days said it was needed because of uncertainty over whether the 
districts ban on capital punishment could be used to block 
extradition of juvenile suspects facing a possible death sentence 
that question is now before a district court 
the 17yearold teenager identified only by the initials om 
could face murder and arson charges in connection with an april 
1988 firebombing of a gadsen ala apartment that took the life of 
a 14monthold boy the teenager is being held here pending a 
decision on alabamas extradition request 
during more than three hours of debate tuesday supporters of 
the measure said a jurisdiction that bans capital punishment should 
not subject a suspect in its custody to the death penalty 
elsewhere others also raised questions about whether the youth 
who is black would receive a fair trial 
it is reprehensible that a jurisdiction would even consider 
applying a death penalty to a juvenile said william lightfoot a 
council member that is not civilized conduct 
another member nadine winter said that by refusing to 
extradite the youth the district could gain a reputation as a 
haven for juveniles accused of serious crimes 
at a recent court hearing relatives of the teenager recounted 
alleged racial abuse by gadsen officials also reviewed at the 
hearing were comments recently made to the washington post by the 
countys only juvenile judge robert e lewis in which lewis 
suggested he thought the teenager likely was involved in the 
firebombing 
the emergency legislation which would apply only to om was 
sought after a recent court hearing left in doubt whether the 
districts existing laws were sufficient to block the extradition 
the teenagers attorney gerald fisher argued the districts 
death penalty ban must be applied by district courts when 
considering interstate juvenile extraditions 
but paul alper representing the district government said a 
nationwide juvenile extradition agreement does not give the 
district discretion to approve or reject requests on the basis of 
whether the juvenile might face the death penalty 
a threejudge panel is considering the case but has not 
indicated when it would rule the supreme court has set precedent 
in adult extradition cases but attorneys involved in the district 
case said there has been no test case involving a juvenile before 
the high court 
