<TEXT>
organized labor is finding itself in a 
struggle because of policies laid out by president carlos salinas 
de gortari to reverse mexicos 7yearold economic crisis 
since taking office dec 1 salinas has insisted on economic 
austerity and uprooted veteran union bosses synonymous with 
corruption 
with the measures that have been taken the leaders are 
cautious said francisco zapata a labor specialist at the 
colegio de mexico a graduate school 
the same thing can happen to them that happened to the oil 
workers 
he was referring to salinas going after oil workers union leader 
joaquin hernandez galicia in january hernandez galicia along with 
45 of his associates and union officials wound up in jail on 
weapons and other charges 
more leaders have toppled in salinas campaign against the 
corruption that impedes economic modernization the most recent was 
carlos jonguitud who had run the national education workers union 
for 17 years but who unlike hernandez galicia had not opposed 
salinas 
jonguituds ouster met only one of the demands of thousands of 
striking teachers nearly a month into the strike which virtually 
shut down the nations public school system the government 
grudgingly offered a 25 percent wage and benefits hike 
the teachers victory seemed to indicate that mexicos workers 
whose paychecks are worth half what they were at the start of the 
economic crisis were starting to awaken and learn to fight for 
themselves 
but when mexico city bus workers tried the same tactic and 
struck for a 50 percent wage increase the government swiftly fired 
all 23000 of them and canceled their union contract salinas made 
it clear he wouldnt permit union pay demands to interfere with his 
plans to check inflation and streamline the economy those plans 
include revamping the moneylosing city bus system 
but salinas faces a delicate situation in trying to retain the 
governments longtime control over labor while modernizing the 
economy 
the symbiotic relationship between union leaders and the 
government monopolized by the institutional revolutionary party 
or pri has buttressed mexicos political system and kept the party 
in power since 1929 
partyaligned union leaders churn out the vote for pri 
candidates and keep workers in line with timely raises and generous 
fringe benefits that include housing recreational facilities and 
discount stores the benefits place priaffiliated unionists a cut 
above independent workers 
that system functioned over more than four decades of steady 
economic growth but as mexicos debt crisis continues and the 
economy remains stagnant salinas has been forced to keep raises to 
a minimum to control inflation 
federal funds for such benefits as health and other government 
services have dried up while public investment in a job market 
that must accept 1 million new workers each year has virtually 
disappeared 
the pri suffered the consequences during the presidential 
elections last july workers didnt turn out the vote in the 
traditional massive numbers and salinas won with just over 50 
percent the lowest ever for a pri presidential candidate numerous 
priaffiliated union candidates lost congressional and other races 
the teachers strike possibly the most serious conflict salinas 
has faced since he took office forced the government to break its 
austerity restraints and increase its wage and benefit offer from 
10 percent to 25 percent 
the government also strongarmed the union hierarchy into 
firstever negotiations with dissidents over control of union 
locals where dissidents are a majority or are strong 
the government sought to justify its higher wage offer by saying 
that teachers salaries had fallen behind inflation but it said 
similar raises would not be extended to other unions 
the onetime concession may work to salinas advantage by 
showing flexibility he provided a means of bringing the estimated 
500000 dissident teachers back into the pri fold 
the mexico city bus workers union which is independent 
managed to obtain a court order permitting fired workers to keep 
their jobs at least temporarily and got the bus system running 
again 
but the government intends to pursue its plan to split up the 
public bus company into cooperatives with workers participating if 
they want to 
</TEXT>
