<TEXT>
for 60 of his 89 years the rev 
arthur le blanc made his missionary rounds in an ox cart then in 
april his bishop ordered him to stop and assigned him a car 
the bishop was just 3 years old when le blanc came here from the 
united states and even had served as his altar boy 
i was ordained the year charles lindbergh flew across the 
atlantic le blanc said then the next year he himself crossed 
the atlantic on a threemonth journey that brought him to this 
island off southeast africa on july 10 1928 
he has since endured countless privations a climate doctors in 
1932 said would kill him and only limited success in converting 
the islanders to roman catholicism other christian missionaries 
havent had much success either since the vast majority of people 
here still cling to traditional ways and to animism a belief that 
inanimate objects have consciousness and personalities 
le blanc devoted his life to trying to sow roman catholism among 
them nevertheless and if he wasnt a big success at that he 
achieved other things that would please a religious man 
six years ago he almost lost his sight a surgical implant has 
helped save it earlier he nearly died from blackwater fever 
but he kept going 
his persistance is incredible in the early 1970s american 
was a dirty word here but he was so accepted that the difficulties 
didnt affect him said the rev joseph shea director of 
personnel for la sallete order to which le blanc belongs 
priests in the united states dont see the results of their 
work le blanc told a reporter here we do 
sipping on a small glass of rum during one of his rare visits to 
the capital le blanc recalled that books magazines electricity 
even vegetables and fruit were luxuries most of the time and he 
spent many years as the only priest in one of several towns on the 
west coast 
two letters would arrive at the same time one asking why the 
other one hadnt been answered he said 
when you get interested in your work you can do without things 
you thought were necessary in the past you like the people your 
companion priests thats the main thing 
im staying until the end 
he doesnt plan to use a us vacation due him this year his 
three brothers and two sisters have died 
le blanc talked of his arrival in madagarscar 
we had no church or even a house so we rented a villagers 
house it was our dormitory our dining room was in another house 
a mile away 
two other priests joined him after he opened the first mission 
in morondova 240 miles by air and until recently a twoday and 
sometimes dangerous drive from antananarivo 
we built a wooden cathedral in morondova sixty men went into 
the forest and cut wood for it it is still in use because the new 
concrete one isnt finished 
his first task was to teach himself the malagasy language and 
local children helped services were conducted in latin but the 
priests read their sermons in malagasy 
wed make all kinds of mistakes but the people were used to 
that and they were so happy we tried 
newly arrived priests now get a sevenmonth course in the 
language 
his initial forays into the scorching heat of the baobab and 
tamarind country around morondava were taken in a palaquin a 
covered litter carried by four men who handed him to a second team 
in shifts without dropping him 
after the government banned this practice he began using an ox 
cart extremely expensive on the small stipends priests earn but 
the only reliable form of transport 
i packed my baggage cooking gear and mass materials into the 
cart along with coffee and sugar i carried no food people gave 
me rice and chicken he said 
most trips were two months or longer dodging ant hills and 
seeking shelter from the maddening ranovory downpours that 
occasionally burst from the usually deep blue skies there were few 
villages or other rest points en route 
you wanted to stop but where 
le blanc reckons he has gone through four or five ox carts and 
an untold number of oxen at one point the us catholic 
missionary vehicle association gave him 1500 for a new cart 
he recalled visiting one village to see a woman who had given up 
the faith to return to her former traditional beliefs 
i tried without success to convince her to return and then 
left her village to resume my trip 
but my ox died and i had to go back to her village to find 
another one the woman said my return was a sign from heaven and 
she confessed he said 
it was thrilling to find one person who seemed to be 
interested who asked a lot of questions 
le blanc has baptized thousands over the years but sometimes he 
would return from a long trip with no new converts or only a 
handful news that wasnt well received at church headquarters 
the people are ferociously individualist and cling to their 
traditional way said shea of the la sallete order 
it is estimated that perhaps only 8 percent of the people in the 
morondava area are christians most of the rest are animists 
ancestor worship is widely practiced in madagascar an island 
whose people have oceanic origins 
in the morondava area several cemetaries display explicit erotic 
funeral art and funerals somtimes include orgies 
visitors to the cemetaries are expected to make a donation to 
the dead usually a sprinkling of rum before entering the spirit 
domain 
</TEXT>
