<TEXT>
the pacific stock exchange plans to file an 
application with the commodity futures trading commission for 
permission to establish a futures market for computer chips 
dale carlson spokesman for the san franciscobased pacific 
stock exchange said monday that the exchange also plans a cash 
chip market the application is to be submitted to the federal 
agency within two weeks 
the exchange appears to be competing with the minneapolisbased 
twin cities board of trade to set up the first chipfutures and 
cash markets in the united states 
last week the twin cities exchange said it hopes to open a cash 
chip market in the fourth quarter of this year and a futures market 
in 1990 
the pacific stock exchange plans to open both markets in the 
first quarter of 1990 according to carlson 
chipfutures trading on the pse would involve critical computer 
memory devices called drams each contract would consist of 1000 
chips 
a cash market would help buyers find the lowest price for chips 
the computer industry has recently experienced problems tied to 
escalating chip prices 
calson while saying pse officials have not seen the minneapolis 
boards plans said the san francisco exchange is better suited to 
chip futures trading because of its location near the nations top 
computer manufacturing area he also cited the pses 100year 
history 
our location near silicon valley and our position as a gateway 
to the pacific rim gives us some strategic advantages said 
carlson 
federal law does not bar two exchanges from trading futures for 
the same product but the market has traditionally gravitated to 
one exchange only 
a buyer and seller under a futures contract agree to exchange a 
given amount of a product for a set price at some time in the 
future the contracts are usually for three six or nine months and 
can be bought for little money down 
the contracts allow buyers and sellers to hedge against future 
price fluctuations because they are guaranteed a set price 
</TEXT>
