<TEXT>
in perhaps no other industry must the producer 
obtain permission from regulators for each individual unit of 
production housing in other words is a very highly regulated 
industry 
housing is also expensive for most people it is the most costly 
item of a lifetime for young couples it is the biggest financial 
hurdle of their lives regulations have a lot to do with that 
situation 
could something be done to lower such costs such as reducing 
regulations 
certainly regulations that proliferate at the local level could 
be thinned out will it be done probably not or if so only by 
bits and pieces 
previous attempts at least have always met with frustration 
there are good and necessary regulations and poor and undesirable 
regulations and no way to separate the two types without endless 
battles in thousands of communities 
still the idea of less regulation is always on the minds of 
builders and their representatives for a simple reason any price 
cut can be translated into more sales and bigger profits to say 
nothing about making housing affordable 
seeking to determine what savings might result from a relaxation 
of local regulations the joint venture for affordable housing a 
program involving the industry and state and local officials 
conducted demonstration projects 
reviewing the results the experimenters concluded that the 
average savings per unit in land and construction cost was 8573 
with the range of savings differing markedly from place to place 
in portland ore for example unit savings amounted to 15647 
for homes in a price range of 50000 to 55000 in elkhart city 
ind the savings amounted to only 855 on a home priced to sell 
between 37500 to 54920 
in general according to the national association of home 
builders the savings were found in four categories 
land use regulations mainly about density development 
standards such as road width sewers and sidewalks construction 
methods such as in allowing new materials and wider spacing of 
studs and streamlined paper processing 
most of the savings in the first category were a result of 
allowing more units to be built on the same amount of land 
reducing not only the land cost per unit but the cost per lot for 
streets and sidewalks 
in some instances local agencies may insist on questionable 
development practices such as requiring suburban residential 
streets to meet the same standards as urban thoroughfares with 
square curbs and wide sidewalks 
do such requirements serve the neighborhood perhaps but maybe 
not wide streets for example may encourage more through traffic 
and higher speeds raising the danger to children playing in the 
neighborhood 
while most localities base their local codes on national models 
they often exercize their right to add amendments or adopt only 
parts that suit them there could also be a bias against 
innovations in materials and techniques 
the home builders report also suggests that economic interests 
and social preferences of existing residents often favor 
limitations to growth sometimes limiting new construction to very 
expensive homes 
in fact it suggests some local regulations wouldnt stand up 
in court but it concedes that the fact they are illegal doesnt 
mean they are not present and effective 
obviously however most local regulations are necessary and 
beneficial for all parties involved in the absence of regulations 
chaotic competition would develop among builders hurting them the 
buyers and the communities 
if there is an answer to the regulatory problem nobody has yet 
stumbled on it it is an allamerican problem snarled in the 
grassroots peculiarities of 9000 local agencies it is democracy 
at its best and worst 
</TEXT>
